      All services validate the same JWT token

  2. Live Demo Steps

  Step A: Show the Login Process

  1. Open browser DevTools (F12) â†’ Network tab
  2. Navigate to your app and click Login
  3. Enter credentials and login
  4. Point out the login request to http://localhost:5000/api/auth/login
  5. Show the response with the JWT token

  Step B: Show Token Storage

  1. Open Application tab (or Storage in Firefox)
  2. Go to Local Storage â†’ http://localhost:4200
  3. Show the stored token: Point to where the JWT is saved
  4. Explain: "This token is used for all subsequent requests to all services"

  Step C: Demonstrate Cross-Service Authentication

  1. Stay in Network tab
  2. Navigate to different pages (Profile, Transfer Requests, Admin Panel)
  3. Filter network requests by "vehicles" or "transfers"
  4. Click on any API request
  5. Show the Headers â†’ Authorization: Bearer eyJhbG...
  6. Explain: "Notice the same token is used for VehicleService API calls"

  Step D: Show Centralized Authorization

  Professor: "How does VehicleService know this token is valid?"

  You: "Let me show you the code..."

  Open VehicleService/Program.cs and show:
  builder.Services.AddAuthentication(JwtBearerDefaults.AuthenticationScheme)
      .AddJwtBearer(options =>
      {
          options.TokenValidationParameters = new TokenValidationParameters
          {
              ValidateIssuer = true,
              ValidateAudience = true,
              ValidateLifetime = true,
              ValidateIssuerSigningKey = true,
              ValidIssuer = builder.Configuration["Jwt:Issuer"],
              ValidAudience = builder.Configuration["Jwt:Audience"],
              IssuerSigningKey = new SymmetricSecurityKey(
                  Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(builder.Configuration["Jwt:Key"]))
          };
      });

  Explain: "All services validate tokens using the same JWT secret from AuthService"

  Step E: Role-Based Access Control Demo

  1. Login as regular user â†’ Show you can access profile, vehicles
  2. Try to access admin panel â†’ Blocked!
  3. Logout and login as admin â†’ Same token mechanism
  4. Show you can now access admin panel
  5. Explain: "One authentication system, different permissions"

  3. Postman/Thunder Client Demo (Technical Proof)

  Show the professor that SSO works even outside the frontend:

  1. Open Postman or Thunder Client
  2. Login via API:
  POST http://localhost:5000/api/auth/login
  {
    "username": "vule123",
    "password": "your-password"
  }
  3. Copy the token from response
  4. Use the same token for multiple services:
  GET http://localhost:5293/api/Vehicles/owner-id/4
  Authorization: Bearer <token>

  GET http://localhost:5293/api/VehicleTransfers/my-requests
  Authorization: Bearer <token>
  5. Explain: "One login, one token, works across all microservices"

  4. Token Expiration Demo (Bonus Points)

  Show what happens when tokens expire:

  1. In AuthService, show the token expiration configuration
  2. Explain: "Tokens expire after X minutes for security"
  3. Show the refresh token mechanism in your code
  4. Optional: Manually set a very short expiration (30 seconds) and show auto-refresh

  5. Key Talking Points

  When explaining SSO to your professor, emphasize:

  âœ… "Single Point of Authentication"
  - "Users authenticate once with AuthService"
  - "All other services trust AuthService's tokens"

  âœ… "Stateless Authentication"
  - "JWT tokens contain all user information"
  - "Services don't need to query AuthService for every request"
  - "This is scalable and performant"

  âœ… "Centralized User Management"
  - "All user accounts managed in one place"
  - "Password changes, role updates affect all services immediately"

  âœ… "Security Benefits"
  - "Token-based, no session storage"
  - "Tokens expire automatically"
  - "Can be revoked centrally"

  6. Preparation Checklist

  Before the demo:
  - Have at least 2 users: one regular, one admin
  - Have some test vehicles and transfers
  - Practice opening DevTools quickly
  - Bookmark the Network tab and Application tab
  - Have the architecture diagram ready
  - Test everything works

  7. Common Professor Questions & Answers

  Q: "What if AuthService goes down?"
  A: "All services would reject requests since they can't validate tokens. In production, we'd use redundant AuthService instances and load balancing."

  Q: "Is this true SSO or just JWT authentication?"
  A: "It's JWT-based SSO. Users authenticate once, and the token works across all microservices. In enterprise SSO (like OAuth2/SAML), the principle is the same - one login, multiple services."

  Q: "How do you prevent token theft?"
  A: "HTTPS in production, short expiration times, refresh tokens, and HTTPOnly cookies for web apps. For this academic project, we demonstrate the core SSO architecture."

  Q: "Why not use OAuth2 or SAML?"
  A: "For a microservices academic project, JWT provides the core SSO functionality. OAuth2 adds complexity mainly needed when integrating third-party applications (like 'Login with Google')."

  ---
  Pro Tip: Practice this flow 2-3 times before the demo so you can do it smoothly without fumbling. Professors love when you can clearly show the token flow and explain the architecture!

  Good luck with your presentation! ðŸŽ“